ternal Cycle, 3) the Secret Cycle, and 4) the Unsurpassed Secret Cycle, also known as the Seminal Heart (\u003cem\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003esnying thig\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/em\u003e). Each of the four self-consciously claims superiority over its predecessors. The lower three cycles (\u003cem\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eskor gsum\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/em\u003e) represent the development of movements culminating in the fourth over a period from the latter half of the 10th century to the first half of the 12th century. Vimalamitra is the dominant 8th-century Indian patron of these texts.\u003c/p\u003e"}],"nested_descriptions":[{"id":"1696","is_primary":"true","title":"An Overview of the Four Cycles"}],"illustrations":[],"associated_resources":{"etymology_count":0,"related_feature_count":4,"description_count":1,"place_count":0,"picture_count":0,"video_count":0,"document_count":0},"created_at":"2013-09-15T04:19:20.000+00:00","updated_at":"2013-09-16T09:10:32.000+00:00"}}